'''Paul Meier''' (July 24, 1924 – August 7, 2011)<ref name=hevesi>{{citation |last=Hevesi |first=Dennis|title=Paul Meier, Statistician Who Revolutionized Medical Trials, Dies at 87 | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 12, 2011 |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/13/health/13meier.html}}</ref> was a [[statistician]] who promoted the use of [[random assignment|randomized trials]] in medicine.<ref>{{cite news | title = Paul Meier, biostatistician and co-inventor of a famous graph, dies at 87 | url = http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/paul-meier-biostatistician-and-co-inventor-of-a-famous-graph-dies-at-87/2011/08/09/gIQAfHBH7I_story.html | author = David Brown | date = August 10, 2011 | publisher = [[Washington Post]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Paul Meier, Obituary | url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/medicine-obituaries/8804883/Paul-Meier.html | date = October 2, 2011 | publisher = [[The Daily Telegraph]]}}</ref>  He is also known for introducing, with Edward L. Kaplan, the [[Kaplan–Meier estimator]],<ref>Kaplan, E. L.; Meier, P.: Nonparametric estimation from incomplete observations. ''J. Amer. Statist. Assn.'' '''53''':457–481, 1958. {{jstor|2281868}}</ref><ref>Kaplan, E.L. in a retrospective on the seminal paper in "This week's citation classic". ''Current Contents'' '''24''', 14 (1983).[http://www.garfield.library.upenn.edu/classics1983/A1983QS51100001.pdf Available from UPenn as PDF.]</ref> a tool for measuring how many patients survive a medical treatment.<ref>{{citation | journal = [[Clinical Trials]] | year = 2004| volume = 1 | page = 131 | url = http://www.hopkinsmedicine.org/bin/m/b/meier.pdf
| title = A conversation with Paul Meier | author = [[Harry M Marks]] | doi = 10.1191/1740774504cn011xx}}</ref>

